    {
      "id": "bc0bdbe91bee4218ada69596c29de5cfac4e2f25",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-13 03:21:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Does landing something like this mean we lose patchless servers\n > again :-(\n\nNo, this change is exactly to avoid potential problems between patched and unpatched kernels.  Instead of removing the EXPORT_SYMBOLs for the bio_integrity_* functions, this change returns them to the pre-patched-kernel state.  Similarly, for the affected data structures, the changes are restructured so that there is not a problem between patched vs. unpatched kernels.\n\nEven without this change, it is still possible to build ldiskfs against an unpatched kernel with autoconf checks.  The goal of this change is to further minimize differences between the kernels.  I don't want to go so far as to say \"ABI compatible\" since I haven't tested that myself, but it is structured to to be binary compatible as much as possible.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d32c92ab7e0c4dc97dae7f8a80c9b10bbad96181",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-13 03:24:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nPS- the ldiskfs-T10PI hardware integration is not possible without the block-* patches, because the unpatched RHEL7 kernel does not have the interfaces to pass down the GRD tags to the driver, but not many people have T10PI hardware so it isn't so critical.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
